```
// lib code
namespace libx
{
    namespace ns1
    {
        struct X1{};
    }

    namespace ns2
    {
        struct X2{};
    }
}
```

Is there a way to qualify all uses of the lib with its global namespace, but omit the nested namespaces? Like so:


```
// user code
auto test()
{
    // using ????

    libx::X1 x1{};
    libx::X2 x2{};
}
```

The only way I can think of is to reopen its global namespace:


```
// user code
namespace libx // reopening lib&#39;s namespace
{
    using namespace ns1;
    using namespace ns2;
}
```

But this can be illegal (e.g. `namespace std` in the standard library) (and even if it&#39;s not explicitly made illegal I think can break the lib now or the future - I mean, there must be a reason why C++ prohibits it for the standard library)  and cannot be done locally (inside a single function for instance)

---

Alternative I thought of:

Rename each of the nested namespace:

```
// user code
auto test()
{
    namespace libx1 = libx::ns1;
    namespace libx2 = libx::ns2;
    
    libx1::X1 x1{};
    libx2::X2 x2{};
}
```

But this has different qualifiers for each nested namespace.

Create a new global namespace where you bring all nested namespaces:

```
//user code:
namespace libx_all
{
    using namespace libx;
    using namespace libx::ns1;
    using namespace libx::ns2;
}

auto test()
{
    namespace libx1 = libx::ns1;
    
    libx_all::X1 x1{};
    libx_all::X2 x2{};
}
```

